submissions.name: Treatment Tracker
submissions.creator: Propublica
submissions.description: Medicare recently released, for the first time, details on 2012 payments to individual doctors and other health professionals serving the 46 million seniors and disabled in its Part B program. Part B covers services as varied as office visits, ambulance mileage, lab tests, and the doctor’s fee for open-heart surgery. Use this tool to find and compare providers.

submissions.creator: The Boston Globe
submissions.description: A look at how President Obama and his family spent their time on Martha’s Vineyard during their 2009, 2010 and 2011 vacations.

submissions.name: Analyzing ticks, town by town
submissions.creator: The Boston Globe
submissions.description: A map showing the number of ticks sent in for DNA analysis by towns in MA

submissions.description: Overview of former Boston Mayor Thomas M. Menino's key term usage in State of the City addresses

submissions.name: Inaugural language
submissions.creator: The Boston Globe
submissions.description: "American inaugural addresses often cover similar ground. They celebrate American values while looking forward to the future, but the vocabulary has changed over the decades.... The following graphs visualize inaugural addresses words. Each dot represents one word. Darker dots indicate more frequent usage. The graph radius represents duration of speech. Common English words have been removed."

submissions.name: Overhauling the school assignment system
submissions.creator: The Boston Globe
submissions.description: "Boston school officials have presented five proposals to revamp the city’s school-assignment system. Mayor Thomas M. Menino has said he would like Boston students to be able to attend schools closer to their homes. Here is a look at the plans."

submissions.name: How much water is in your scallop?
submissions.creator: The Boston Globe
submissions.description: "A Globe investigation of 21 grocery stores and seafood markets across Massachusetts found scallops with water levels far exceeding industry standards."

submissions.name: Obama stayed on-script at DNC
submissions.creator: The Boston Globe
submissions.description: A comparison between President Obama's prepared remarks to the DNC versus the actual speech.

submissions.name: How MIT brainpower returned a dancer to the stage
submissions.creator: The Boston Globe
submissions.description: "BioM, a Bedford company founded in 2007 by an MIT professor, has created a prosthetic ankle that supplies power during walking and produces a more natural gait. The ankle is fitted based on the amputee’s ideal stride, to minimize gait abnormalities that lead to health problems." In this interactive the user can see how the prosthetic ankle works at different stages of a stride.

submissions.name: One Year, One City
submissions.creator: The Boston Globe
submissions.description: "On April 15, 2013, their lives intersected at the Marathon. One year later, they returned to the scene for a historic photo shoot."

submissions.name: How Dark Money Flows Through the Koch Network
submissions.creator: Propublica

submissions.name: ER Wait Watcher
submissions.creator: Propublica
submissions.description: An emergency room locator paired with a comparison of wait times across states.

submissions.name: How Well Did FEMA's Maps Predict Sandy's Flooding?
submissions.creator: Propublica
submissions.description: "When Superstorm Sandy struck New York and New Jersey last year, the accuracy of FEMA’s flood-risk maps for the area varied widely. In some cases, the data behind the maps dated as far back to the 1970s. The maps help guide development and set flood insurance rates, so many property owners were left unprepared for the flooding. Click a county below to see more about FEMA’s data for that county, including the age of its maps and how well they predicted Sandy’s extent."

submissions.name: The new faces of City Hall
submissions.creator: The Boston Globe
submissions.description: A graphic illustrating the changing structure of the City of Boston under the new Mayor. Interesting examples including print, web and mobile.

submissions.name: Evolution of a tycoon
submissions.creator: The Boston Globe
submissions.description: Taxi magnate Edward J. Tutunjian owns by far the largest share of Boston cabs: 372, or one in five. In this visualization we get an idea of the timeline, as well as the size and estimated value of the fleet in the current market.

submissions.name: Votes up for grabs in Boston mayoral race
submissions.creator: The Boston Globe
submissions.description: The results of Boston's Mayoral Election.

submissions.name: The Most Stylish Bostonians 2014
submissions.creator: The Boston Globe
submissions.description: The Globe’s ninth annual list of tastemakers.

submissions.name: The Opportunity Gap
submissions.creator: Propublica
submissions.description: "This database includes all public schools in districts with more than 3,000 students from the 2009-2010 school year -- about three-quarters of all such students in the country. Use it to find out how well your state provides poor and wealthier schools equal access to advanced classes that researchers say will help them later in life."

submissions.name: Dollars for Docs
submissions.creator: Propublica
submissions.description: "In recent years, drug companies have started releasing details of the payments they make to doctors and other health professionals for promotional talks, research and consulting. As of 2012, 15 companies published the information, most because of legal settlements. Use this tool to search for payments."

submissions.name: Message Machine: Reverse-Engineering the 2012 Campaign
submissions.creator: Propublica
submissions.description: "Political campaigns send many variations of each email to supporters. We've been collecting emails from political campaigns and tracking the variations. Here you can explore those emails."

submissions.name: Dialysis: The High Costs and Hidden Perils of a Treatment Guaranteed to All
submissions.creator: Propublica
submissions.description: "This site is for dialysis patients and others who want to learn about the quality of care at individual dialysis clinics. Among other things, you can learn how often patients treated at a facility have been hospitalized, report certain types of infections or are placed on the transplant list. The information is submitted by facilities and collected by contractors of the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services, the federal agency that oversees most dialysis care."

submissions.name: Where Congress Stands on Guns
submissions.creator: Propublica
submissions.description: "In the aftermath of the Newtown tragedy, Congress has considered new national gun control measures. We present where each member of Congress stands on guns."

submissions.name: Has the Gov't Lied on Snooping? Let's Go to the Videotape
submissions.creator: Propublica
submissions.description:
"Since Edward Snowden leaked a trove of documents detailing the NSA's sweeping surveillance programs, Director of National Intelligence James Clapper acknowledged that part of his congressional testimony in March was "erroneous." But that's not the only questionable comment by administration officials about the programs.

Here are six claims by administration officials about NSA surveillance that have been undermined by recent disclosures."

submissions.name: NSA Surveillance Lawsuit Tracker
submissions.creator: Propublica
submissions.description: "The recent disclosure of sweeping surveillance by NSA whistleblower Edward Snowden has prompted a new wave of legal challenges to the U.S. government's intelligence-gathering programs. Here is a list of key legal challenges to government surveillance and secrecy. "

submissions.name: Mass Surveillance in America: A Timeline of Loosening Laws and Practices
submissions.creator: Propublica
submissions.description: A historical overview of the changing surveillance laws in America

submissions.name: Is It Better to Rent or Buy?
submissions.creator: The New York Times
submissions.description: "The choice between buying a home and renting one is among the biggest financial decisions that many adults make. But the costs of buying are more varied and complicated than for renting, making it hard to tell which is a better deal. To help you answer this question, our calculator takes the most important costs associated with buying a house and computes the equivalent monthly rent. "

submissions.name: Front Row to Fashion Week
submissions.creator: The New York Times
submissions.description: "Of the hundreds of fall 2014 collections shown during New York Fashion Week, here are the ones that left the biggest impressions on fashion editors as they headed off to the next round of shows, in London, Milan and Paris."

submissions.name: Temp Worker Regulations Around the World
submissions.creator: Propublica
submissions.description: "The United States has some of the weakest labor protections for temp workers in the developed world. Other countries have adopted regulations limiting the length of temp assignments, guaranteeing equal pay for equal work and restricting companies from hiring temps for hazardous tasks. Here, we map out how countries compare based on data compiled by the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, which produces research on behalf of the world’s industrialized nations."

submissions.name: The Department of Labor’s Internship Investigations
submissions.creator: Propublica
submissions.description: "In 2010, the Labor Department issued a new fact sheet clarifying when an intern needs to be paid under federal labor law. We collected the case files for the internship investigations the Labor Department concluded in the three years after issuing new guidelines."

submissions.name: School Segregation after Brown
submissions.creator: Propublica
submissions.description:
"
   Hundreds of school districts were placed under court order to desegregate following the Supreme Court’s 1954 Brown v. Board of Education ruling. Many communities do not know the status of these orders. Use this tool to find out whether your district is or ever was under a desegregation order, and also to look at the levels of integration and segregation in your schools. "

submissions.name: Nursing Home Inspect
submissions.creator: Propublica
submissions.description:
"By Charles Ornstein and Lena Groeger, ProPublica. Data updated March 2014.

Use this tool to compare nursing homes in a state based on the deficiencies cited by regulators and the penalties imposed in the past three years. You can also search over 60,000 nursing home inspection reports to look for trends or patterns. "

submissions.name: How Much Acetaminophen Are You Taking?
submissions.creator: Propublica
submissions.description: "Many common over-the-counter drugs contain acetaminophen. Taking more than one at the same time increases your chance of “double-dipping” -- accidentally overdosing. Use this tool to find out which of the drugs in your medicine cabinet contains acetaminophen -- and how much. This is not meant to be medical advice. Toxic levels vary by individual. Call your doctor if you think you’ve overdosed, even if you don’t show medical symptoms."

submissions.name: Short Track
submissions.creator: The New York Times
submissions.description: "On a track crowded with skaters, these racers have to accelerate in the turns and pass when the moment is just right."

submissions.name: For Eli Manning, 150 Games and Counting
submissions.creator: The New York Times
submissions.description: "On Sunday, Manning will start his 150th consecutive game for the Giants. Below, how his streak compares to the streaks of nearly 500 quarterbacks who have started a game since 1970."

submissions.name: Which Team Do You Cheer For? An N.B.A. Fan Map
submissions.creator: The New York Times
submissions.description: A US Map colored by the basketball teams being cheered for in those regions

submissions.name: A Vision of the Future From Those Likely to Invent It
submissions.creator: The New York Times

submissions.name: Fewer Helmets, More Deaths
submissions.creator: The New York Times
submissions.description: More states are being pressured to repeal their universal motorcycle helmet laws. But when those laws are changed, the number of fatalities starts to rise immediately.

submissions.name: The Refugee Project
submissions.creator: Hyperakt, Ekene Ijeoma, Oak
submissions.description: "The Refugee Project is a narrative, temporal map of refugee migrations since 1975. We’ve used UN data to visualize refugee volumes over time and added a layer of historical content to help explain the events that caused some of the largest refugee movements of the last four decades."

submissions.name: Reporter App
submissions.creator: Nicholas Felton
submissions.description: "Reporter is a new application for understanding the things you care about. With a few randomly timed surveys each day, Reporter can illuminate aspects of your life that might be otherwise unmeasurable."

submissions.name: Taking the Battle to the States
submissions.creator: The New York Times
submissions.description: "Republicans or Democrats have single-party control of both the legislature and the governor’s office in 36 states, the most in six decades. Lawmakers in these states have been seeking to reshape government policy in recent years, from legalizing same-sex marriage to restricting labor unions. Some of these laws were passed after the rapid rise of single-party control in 2010; others have been in place for years. Below is a look at where states stand on some key issues."

submissions.name: Who Will Win The Senate?
submissions.creator: The New York Times
submissions.description: "According to our statistical election-forecasting machine, the Democrats have a slight edge, with about a 61% chance of retaining a majority."

submissions.name: Bud’s Story, from the Records
submissions.creator: Propublica
submissions.description: Private Arthur ‘Bud’ Kelder died as a POW in the Philippines during World War II. His parents always hoped that his body would eventually be sent home. But despite clues, the military has never recovered his remains. Here are letters and others documents from his case from 1941 to 1950. The documents and photographs below are either from the National Archive or courtesy of John Eakin."

submissions.name: Explore the College of Cardinals
submissions.creator: The Boston Globe
submissions.description: "With the resignation of Pope Benedict XVI, the College of Cardinals is convening to select the new leader of the Catholic Church. Use this graphic to learn more about the cardinals who will select the next pope."

submissions.name: China’s Memory Hole: The Images Erased From Sina Weibo
submissions.creator: Propublica
submissions.description: "ProPublica has been collecting images that have been deleted by censors from Sina Weibo, "China’s Twitter," since May. We gathered a team of people proficient in Mandarin to read and interpret 527 deleted images collected during a two-week window this summer. The images provide a window into the Chinese elite’s self-image and its fears, as well as a lens through which to understand China’s vast system of censorship."

submissions.name: Sun
submissions.creator: Jakob Henner
submissions.description: A web based mobile only weather application.

submissions.name: 984 Ways the United States Can Advance to the Next Round of the World Cup
submissions.creator: The New York Times
submissions.description: A table showing the most likely scenarios for the United States to advance to the next round in the World Cup.

submissions.name: Leagues of the World Cup
submissions.creator: The Washington Post
submissions.description: "Each of the 32 World Cup countries has a professional soccer league, but you wouldn’t know it by looking at some rosters. More than two-thirds of participants in this year’s tournament spend the rest of the year in the powerhouse leagues of Europe."

submissions.name: Record-Setting Effort by Howard, but Belgium Ousts U.S.
submissions.creator: The New York Times
submissions.description: An interactive overview of the BEL & USA World cup game goal attempts
